# FreeCRM General Guidelines

## Change approval

- **Propose-only mode**: describe edits and show patches; do not modify files or data until the user explicitly accepts.
- Read-only investigation (Read/Grep/SemanticSearch/MCP SELECT/logs) is always allowed.
- Never run `git` without consent.

## Modernization stance

FreeCRM is being actively modernized. **No fallbacks. No compat shims. No parallel code paths.**

- When a contract changes, update every call site in the same change.
- When something is replaced, delete the old version in the same change (or as an explicit final step within it). Legacy code does not get to "stick around for now".
- No `class_alias()`, no `if ($useLegacy) â€¦ else â€¦` branches, no "kept for backward compatibility" comments.
- Internal APIs, class hierarchies, table columns, and module contracts may all be broken freely. What we preserve is **data integrity** and **user-facing flows** (the screens / APIs / cron jobs people actually use).
- For larger refactors and feature changes, use the CR templates `cr-create.mdc` and `cr-review.mdc`, which encode this stance.

## Editing

- Prefer modifying existing files; do not create new files unless necessary.
- Never use `class_alias()` or similar aliases (see Modernization stance).
- For many edits in one file, prefer `sed`.
- Continue on partial errors â€” partial fixes are valuable.
- **Minify frontend assets in the same change**: after editing any non-minified `.js` or `.css` under `public/`, run `npm run minify-js -- <file>` or `npm run minify-css -- <file>` and commit the `.min.*` output together with the source. Never edit `.min.js` / `.min.css` by hand. Details: `frontend-assets.mdc`.

## Agent autonomy

- Do not ask the user to do work you can do (paste logs, list files, choose between equivalent options).
- Only ask when truly blocked (missing credentials, destructive/irreversible actions, real ambiguity).

## Code comments

- **Explain why, never what.** No narrating comments (`// increment counter`, `// loop users`, `// return result`). Good names + types > prose.
- No filler PHPDoc, no commented-out code, no stale comments. Applies to PHP, JS, Smarty `.tpl`, SQL â€” everywhere.
- Details and exceptions: `php-coding-standards.mdc` â†’ Documentation.

## Deployment (one-liner)

- **`https://dev.itconnect.pl` = local dev** â€” same bind-mounted repo, same Docker `web`/`app`/`cron`/`db` stack as WSL (`docker compose`). Not a remote server; code/DB changes apply immediately (no deploy). Distinct from **`test.itconnect.pl`** (`/opt/freecrm`, remote).
- Deployed on `test.itconnect.pl` at `/opt/freecrm` (`web`, `app`, `cron`, `db`); MariaDB at `127.0.0.1:3306` on the server.
- **Never run `scripts/sync-freecrm.sh` (`pushsrc` / `pushdb` / `pushall` / `pulldb`) without explicit user approval** â€” even when a task changes runtime behavior. Offer deploy as a follow-up; wait for confirmation before syncing to the server.
- After approval: use the **Standard deploy** recipe in `deployment.mdc` (do not read `sync-freecrm.sh`). LinkAction www: see `link-action.mdc` (Cyberfolks rsync + merge `_link_action/config.php`).
- MCP browser (`cursor-ide-browser`) uses `https://dev.itconnect.pl` for dev web checks â€” that **is** local. WSL cannot reach `http://localhost` for this stack; never SSH to test server for local web QA.

For deeper testing/log details see `error-checking.mdc`. For deployment specifics see `deployment.mdc`.

## Focused JS playbook

- For ListView/list-page JavaScript work, use `listview-javascript-playbook.mdc` as the first reference (boot flow, core files, safe edit strategy, debugging checklist, and minification expectations).
- For DetailView/detail-page JavaScript work, use `detailview-javascript-playbook.mdc` as the first reference (boot flow, core files, safe edit strategy, navigation context, and minification expectations).
- For RelatedList/related-tab JavaScript work, use `relatedlist-javascript-playbook.mdc` as the first reference (detail integration, core files, safe edit strategy, reload/event lifecycle, and minification expectations).

## Persisting learnings (end of session)

If during the session you discovered a reusable, non-obvious fact (a Docker quirk, a fix pattern, a file location, a working command) that would save time next session, propose adding it to the most relevant `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` before wrapping up. Prefer extending an existing rule over creating a new file. Skip silently if nothing reached that bar or it's already covered.
